.SH "SPECIAL START-OF-PATTERN ITEMS"

.LP
Some options that can be passed to \fB\fIcompile/2\fR\&\fR\& can also be set by special items at the start of a pattern\&. These are not Perl-compatible, but are provided to make these options accessible to pattern writers who are not able to change the program that processes the pattern\&. Any number of these items can appear, but they must all be together right at the start of the pattern string, and the letters must be in upper case\&.
.LP
\fIUTF Support\fR\&
.LP
Unicode support is basically UTF-8 based\&. To use Unicode characters, you either call \fB\fIcompile/2\fR\&\fR\& or \fB\fIrun/3\fR\&\fR\& with option \fIunicode\fR\&, or the pattern must start with one of these special sequences:
.LP
.nf

(*UTF8)
(*UTF)
.fi
.LP
Both options give the same effect, the input string is interpreted as UTF-8\&. Notice that with these instructions, the automatic conversion of lists to UTF-8 is not performed by the \fIre\fR\& functions\&. Therefore, using these sequences is not recommended\&. Add option \fIunicode\fR\& when running \fB\fIcompile/2\fR\&\fR\& instead\&.
.LP
Some applications that allow their users to supply patterns can wish to restrict them to non-UTF data for security reasons\&. If option \fInever_utf\fR\& is set at compile time, (*UTF), and so on, are not allowed, and their appearance causes an error\&.
.LP
\fIUnicode Property Support\fR\&
.LP
The following is another special sequence that can appear at the start of a pattern:
.LP
.nf

(*UCP)
.fi
.LP
This has the same effect as setting option \fIucp\fR\&: it causes sequences such as \\d and \\w to use Unicode properties to determine character types, instead of recognizing only characters with codes < 256 through a lookup table\&.
.LP
\fIDisabling Startup Optimizations\fR\&
.LP
If a pattern starts with \fI(*NO_START_OPT)\fR\&, it has the same effect as setting option \fIno_start_optimize\fR\& at compile time\&.
.LP
\fINewline Conventions\fR\&
.LP
PCRE supports five conventions for indicating line breaks in strings: a single CR (carriage return) character, a single LF (line feed) character, the two-character sequence CRLF, any of the three preceding, and any Unicode newline sequence\&.
.LP
A newline convention can also be specified by starting a pattern string with one of the following five sequences:
.RS 2
.TP 2
.B
(*CR):
Carriage return
.TP 2
.B
(*LF):
Line feed
.TP 2
.B
(*CRLF):
>Carriage return followed by line feed
.TP 2
.B
(*ANYCRLF):
Any of the three above
.TP 2
.B
(*ANY):
All Unicode newline sequences
.RE
.LP
These override the default and the options specified to \fB\fIcompile/2\fR\&\fR\&\&. For example, the following pattern changes the convention to CR:
.LP
.nf

(*CR)a.b
.fi
.LP
This pattern matches \fIa\\nb\fR\&, as LF is no longer a newline\&. If more than one of them is present, the last one is used\&.
.LP
The newline convention affects where the circumflex and dollar assertions are true\&. It also affects the interpretation of the dot metacharacter when \fIdotall\fR\& is not set, and the behavior of \\N\&. However, it does not affect what the \\R escape sequence matches\&. By default, this is any Unicode newline sequence, for Perl compatibility\&. However, this can be changed; see the description of \\R in section \fBNewline Sequences\fR\&\&. A change of the \\R setting can be combined with a change of the newline convention\&.
.LP
\fISetting Match and Recursion Limits\fR\&
.LP
The caller of \fB\fIrun/3\fR\&\fR\& can set a limit on the number of times the internal match() function is called and on the maximum depth of recursive calls\&. These facilities are provided to catch runaway matches that are provoked by patterns with huge matching trees (a typical example is a pattern with nested unlimited repeats) and to avoid running out of system stack by too much recursion\&. When one of these limits is reached, \fIpcre_exec()\fR\& gives an error return\&. The limits can also be set by items at the start of the pattern of the following forms:
.LP
.nf

(*LIMIT_MATCH=d)
(*LIMIT_RECURSION=d)
.fi
.LP
Here d is any number of decimal digits\&. However, the value of the setting must be less than the value set by the caller of \fIrun/3\fR\& for it to have any effect\&. That is, the pattern writer can lower the limit set by the programmer, but not raise it\&. If there is more than one setting of one of these limits, the lower value is used\&.
.LP
The default value for both the limits is 10,000,000 in the Erlang VM\&. Notice that the recursion limit does not affect the stack depth of the VM, as PCRE for Erlang is compiled in such a way that the match function never does recursion on the C stack\&.
.SH "CHARACTERS AND METACHARACTERS"

.LP
A regular expression is a pattern that is matched against a subject string from left to right\&. Most characters stand for themselves in a pattern and match the corresponding characters in the subject\&. As a trivial example, the following pattern matches a portion of a subject string that is identical to itself:
.LP
.nf

The quick brown fox
.fi
.LP
When caseless matching is specified (option \fIcaseless\fR\&), letters are matched independently of case\&.
.LP
The power of regular expressions comes from the ability to include alternatives and repetitions in the pattern\&. These are encoded in the pattern by the use of \fImetacharacters\fR\&, which do not stand for themselves but instead are interpreted in some special way\&.
.LP
Two sets of metacharacters exist: those that are recognized anywhere in the pattern except within square brackets, and those that are recognized within square brackets\&. Outside square brackets, the metacharacters are as follows:
.RS 2
.TP 2
.B
\\:
General escape character with many uses
.TP 2
.B
^:
Assert start of string (or line, in multiline mode) 
.TP 2
.B
$:
Assert end of string (or line, in multiline mode)
.TP 2
.B
\&.:
Match any character except newline (by default)
.TP 2
.B
[:
Start character class definition
.TP 2
.B
|:
Start of alternative branch
.TP 2
.B
(:
Start subpattern
.TP 2
.B
):
End subpattern
.TP 2
.B
?:
Extends the meaning of (, also 0 or 1 quantifier, also quantifier minimizer
.TP 2
.B
*:
0 or more quantifiers
.TP 2
.B
+:
1 or more quantifier, also "possessive quantifier" 
.TP 2
.B
{:
Start min/max quantifier
.RE
.LP
Part of a pattern within square brackets is called a "character class"\&. The following are the only metacharacters in a character class:
.RS 2
.TP 2
.B
\\:
General escape character
.TP 2
.B
^:
Negate the class, but only if the first character
.TP 2
.B
-:
Indicates character range
.TP 2
.B
[:
Posix character class (only if followed by Posix syntax) 
.TP 2
.B
]:
Terminates the character class
.RE
.LP
The following sections describe the use of each metacharacter\&.
.SH "BACKSLASH"

.LP
The backslash character has many uses\&. First, if it is followed by a character that is not a number or a letter, it takes away any special meaning that a character can have\&. This use of backslash as an escape character applies both inside and outside character classes\&.
.LP
For example, if you want to match a * character, you write \\* in the pattern\&. This escaping action applies if the following character would otherwise be interpreted as a metacharacter, so it is always safe to precede a non-alphanumeric with backslash to specify that it stands for itself\&. In particular, if you want to match a backslash, write \\\\\&.
.LP
In \fIunicode\fR\& mode, only ASCII numbers and letters have any special meaning after a backslash\&. All other characters (in particular, those whose code points are > 127) are treated as literals\&.
.LP
If a pattern is compiled with option \fIextended\fR\&, whitespace in the pattern (other than in a character class) and characters between a # outside a character class and the next newline are ignored\&. An escaping backslash can be used to include a whitespace or # character as part of the pattern\&.
.LP
To remove the special meaning from a sequence of characters, put them between \\Q and \\E\&. This is different from Perl in that $ and @ are handled as literals in \\Q\&.\&.\&.\\E sequences in PCRE, while $ and @ cause variable interpolation in Perl\&. Notice the following examples:
.LP
.nf

Pattern            PCRE matches   Perl matches

\\Qabc$xyz\\E        abc$xyz        abc followed by the contents of $xyz
\\Qabc\\$xyz\\E       abc\\$xyz       abc\\$xyz
\\Qabc\\E\\$\\Qxyz\\E   abc$xyz        abc$xyz
.fi
.LP
The \\Q\&.\&.\&.\\E sequence is recognized both inside and outside character classes\&. An isolated \\E that is not preceded by \\Q is ignored\&. If \\Q is not followed by \\E later in the pattern, the literal interpretation continues to the end of the pattern (that is, \\E is assumed at the end)\&. If the isolated \\Q is inside a character class, this causes an error, as the character class is not terminated\&.
.LP
\fINon-Printing Characters\fR\&
.LP
A second use of backslash provides a way of encoding non-printing characters in patterns in a visible manner\&. There is no restriction on the appearance of non-printing characters, apart from the binary zero that terminates a pattern\&. When a pattern is prepared by text editing, it is often easier to use one of the following escape sequences than the binary character it represents:
.RS 2
.TP 2
.B
\\a:
Alarm, that is, the BEL character (hex 07)
.TP 2
.B
\\cx:
"Control-x", where x is any ASCII character
.TP 2
.B
\\e:
Escape (hex 1B)
.TP 2
.B
\\f:
Form feed (hex 0C)
.TP 2
.B
\\n:
Line feed (hex 0A)
.TP 2
.B
\\r:
Carriage return (hex 0D)
.TP 2
.B
\\t:
Tab (hex 09)
.TP 2
.B
\\ddd:
Character with octal code ddd, or back reference 
.TP 2
.B
\\xhh:
Character with hex code hh
.TP 2
.B
\\x{hhh\&.\&.}:
Character with hex code hhh\&.\&.
.RE
.LP
The precise effect of \\cx on ASCII characters is as follows: if x is a lowercase letter, it is converted to upper case\&. Then bit 6 of the character (hex 40) is inverted\&. Thus \\cA to \\cZ become hex 01 to hex 1A (A is 41, Z is 5A), but \\c{ becomes hex 3B ({ is 7B), and \\c; becomes hex 7B (; is 3B)\&. If the data item (byte or 16-bit value) following \\c has a value > 127, a compile-time error occurs\&. This locks out non-ASCII characters in all modes\&.
.LP
The \\c facility was designed for use with ASCII characters, but with the extension to Unicode it is even less useful than it once was\&.
.LP
By default, after \\x, from zero to two hexadecimal digits are read (letters can be in upper or lower case)\&. Any number of hexadecimal digits can appear between \\x{ and }, but the character code is constrained as follows:
.RS 2
.TP 2
.B
8-bit non-Unicode mode:
< 0x100
.TP 2
.B
8-bit UTF-8 mode:
< 0x10ffff and a valid code point
.RE
.LP
Invalid Unicode code points are the range 0xd800 to 0xdfff (the so-called "surrogate" code points), and 0xffef\&.
.LP
If characters other than hexadecimal digits appear between \\x{ and }, or if there is no terminating }, this form of escape is not recognized\&. Instead, the initial \\x is interpreted as a basic hexadecimal escape, with no following digits, giving a character whose value is zero\&.
.LP
Characters whose value is < 256 can be defined by either of the two syntaxes for \\x\&. There is no difference in the way they are handled\&. For example, \\xdc is the same as \\x{dc}\&.
.LP
After \\0 up to two further octal digits are read\&. If there are fewer than two digits, only those that are present are used\&. Thus the sequence \\0\\x\\07 specifies two binary zeros followed by a BEL character (code value 7)\&. Ensure to supply two digits after the initial zero if the pattern character that follows is itself an octal digit\&.
.LP
The handling of a backslash followed by a digit other than 0 is complicated\&. Outside a character class, PCRE reads it and any following digits as a decimal number\&. If the number is < 10, or if there have been at least that many previous capturing left parentheses in the expression, the entire sequence is taken as a \fIback reference\fR\&\&. A description of how this works is provided later, following the discussion of parenthesized subpatterns\&.
.LP
Inside a character class, or if the decimal number is > 9 and there have not been that many capturing subpatterns, PCRE re-reads up to three octal digits following the backslash, and uses them to generate a data character\&. Any subsequent digits stand for themselves\&. The value of the character is constrained in the same way as characters specified in hexadecimal\&. For example:
.RS 2
.TP 2
.B
\\040:
Another way of writing an ASCII space
.TP 2
.B
\\40:
The same, provided there are < 40 previous capturing subpatterns
.TP 2
.B
\\7:
Always a back reference
.TP 2
.B
\\11:
Can be a back reference, or another way of writing a tab
.TP 2
.B
\\011:
Always a tab
.TP 2
.B
\\0113:
A tab followed by character "3"
.TP 2
.B
\\113:
Can be a back reference, otherwise the character with octal code 113 
.TP 2
.B
\\377:
Can be a back reference, otherwise value 255 (decimal)
.TP 2
.B
\\81:
Either a back reference, or a binary zero followed by the two characters "8" and "1"
.RE
.LP
Notice that octal values >= 100 must not be introduced by a leading zero, as no more than three octal digits are ever read\&.
.LP
All the sequences that define a single character value can be used both inside and outside character classes\&. Also, inside a character class, \\b is interpreted as the backspace character (hex 08)\&.
.LP
\\N is not allowed in a character class\&. \\B, \\R, and \\X are not special inside a character class\&. Like other unrecognized escape sequences, they are treated as the literal characters "B", "R", and "X"\&. Outside a character class, these sequences have different meanings\&.
.LP
\fIUnsupported Escape Sequences\fR\&
.LP
In Perl, the sequences \\l, \\L, \\u, and \\U are recognized by its string handler and used to modify the case of following characters\&. PCRE does not support these escape sequences\&.
.LP
\fIAbsolute and Relative Back References\fR\&
.LP
The sequence \\g followed by an unsigned or a negative number, optionally enclosed in braces, is an absolute or relative back reference\&. A named back reference can be coded as \\g{name}\&. Back references are discussed later, following the discussion of parenthesized subpatterns\&.
.LP
\fIAbsolute and Relative Subroutine Calls\fR\&
.LP
For compatibility with Oniguruma, the non-Perl syntax \\g followed by a name or a number enclosed either in angle brackets or single quotes, is alternative syntax for referencing a subpattern as a "subroutine"\&. Details are discussed later\&. Notice that \\g{\&.\&.\&.} (Perl syntax) and \\g<\&.\&.\&.> (Oniguruma syntax) are \fInot\fR\& synonymous\&. The former is a back reference and the latter is a subroutine call\&.
.LP
\fIGeneric Character Types\fR\&
.LP
Another use of backslash is for specifying generic character types:
.RS 2
.TP 2
.B
\\d:
Any decimal digit
.TP 2
.B
\\D:
Any character that is not a decimal digit
.TP 2
.B
\\h:
Any horizontal whitespace character
.TP 2
.B
\\H:
Any character that is not a horizontal whitespace character
.TP 2
.B
\\s:
Any whitespace character
.TP 2
.B
\\S:
Any character that is not a whitespace character 
.TP 2
.B
\\v:
Any vertical whitespace character
.TP 2
.B
\\V:
Any character that is not a vertical whitespace character
.TP 2
.B
\\w:
Any "word" character
.TP 2
.B
\\W:
Any "non-word" character
.RE
.LP
There is also the single sequence \\N, which matches a non-newline character\&. This is the same as the "\&." metacharacter when \fIdotall\fR\& is not set\&. Perl also uses \\N to match characters by name, but PCRE does not support this\&.
.LP
Each pair of lowercase and uppercase escape sequences partitions the complete set of characters into two disjoint sets\&. Any given character matches one, and only one, of each pair\&. The sequences can appear both inside and outside character classes\&. They each match one character of the appropriate type\&. If the current matching point is at the end of the subject string, all fail, as there is no character to match\&.
.LP
For compatibility with Perl, \\s does not match the VT character (code 11)\&. This makes it different from the Posix "space" class\&. The \\s characters are HT (9), LF (10), FF (12), CR (13), and space (32)\&. If "use locale;" is included in a Perl script, \\s can match the VT character\&. In PCRE, it never does\&.
.LP
A "word" character is an underscore or any character that is a letter or a digit\&. By default, the definition of letters and digits is controlled by the PCRE low-valued character tables, in Erlang\&'s case (and without option \fIunicode\fR\&), the ISO Latin-1 character set\&.
.LP
By default, in \fIunicode\fR\& mode, characters with values > 255, that is, all characters outside the ISO Latin-1 character set, never match \\d, \\s, or \\w, and always match \\D, \\S, and \\W\&. These sequences retain their original meanings from before UTF support was available, mainly for efficiency reasons\&. However, if option \fIucp\fR\& is set, the behavior is changed so that Unicode properties are used to determine character types, as follows:
.RS 2
.TP 2
.B
\\d:
Any character that \\p{Nd} matches (decimal digit) 
.TP 2
.B
\\s:
Any character that \\p{Z} matches, plus HT, LF, FF, CR 
.TP 2
.B
\\w:
Any character that \\p{L} or \\p{N} matches, plus underscore
.RE
.LP
The uppercase escapes match the inverse sets of characters\&. Notice that \\d matches only decimal digits, while \\w matches any Unicode digit, any Unicode letter, and underscore\&. Notice also that \fIucp\fR\& affects \\b and \\B, as they are defined in terms of \\w and \\W\&. Matching these sequences is noticeably slower when \fIucp\fR\& is set\&.
.LP
The sequences \\h, \\H, \\v, and \\V are features that were added to Perl in release 5\&.10\&. In contrast to the other sequences, which match only ASCII characters by default, these always match certain high-valued code points, regardless if \fIucp\fR\& is set\&.
.LP
The following are the horizontal space characters:
.RS 2
.TP 2
.B
U+0009:
Horizontal tab (HT)
.TP 2
.B
U+0020:
Space
.TP 2
.B
U+00A0:
Non-break space
.TP 2
.B
U+1680:
Ogham space mark
.TP 2
.B
U+180E:
Mongolian vowel separator
.TP 2
.B
U+2000:
En quad
.TP 2
.B
U+2001:
Em quad
.TP 2
.B
U+2002:
En space
.TP 2
.B
U+2003:
Em space
.TP 2
.B
U+2004:
Three-per-em space
.TP 2
.B
U+2005:
Four-per-em space
.TP 2
.B
U+2006:
Six-per-em space
.TP 2
.B
U+2007:
Figure space
.TP 2
.B
U+2008:
Punctuation space
.TP 2
.B
U+2009:
Thin space
.TP 2
.B
U+200A:
Hair space
.TP 2
.B
U+202F:
Narrow no-break space
.TP 2
.B
U+205F:
Medium mathematical space
.TP 2
.B
U+3000:
Ideographic space
.RE
.LP
The following are the vertical space characters:
.RS 2
.TP 2
.B
U+000A:
Line feed (LF)
.TP 2
.B
U+000B:
Vertical tab (VT)
.TP 2
.B
U+000C:
Form feed (FF)
.TP 2
.B
U+000D:
Carriage return (CR)
.TP 2
.B
U+0085:
Next line (NEL)
.TP 2
.B
U+2028:
Line separator
.TP 2
.B
U+2029:
Paragraph separator
.RE
.LP
In 8-bit, non-UTF-8 mode, only the characters with code points < 256 are relevant\&.
.LP
\fINewline Sequences\fR\&
.LP
Outside a character class, by default, the escape sequence \\R matches any Unicode newline sequence\&. In non-UTF-8 mode, \\R is equivalent to the following:
.LP
.nf

(?>\\r\\n|\\n|\\x0b|\\f|\\r|\\x85)
.fi
.LP
This is an example of an "atomic group", details are provided below\&.
.LP
This particular group matches either the two-character sequence CR followed by LF, or one of the single characters LF (line feed, U+000A), VT (vertical tab, U+000B), FF (form feed, U+000C), CR (carriage return, U+000D), or NEL (next line, U+0085)\&. The two-character sequence is treated as a single unit that cannot be split\&.
.LP
In Unicode mode, two more characters whose code points are > 255 are added: LS (line separator, U+2028) and PS (paragraph separator, U+2029)\&. Unicode character property support is not needed for these characters to be recognized\&.
.LP
\\R can be restricted to match only CR, LF, or CRLF (instead of the complete set of Unicode line endings) by setting option \fIbsr_anycrlf\fR\& either at compile time or when the pattern is matched\&. (BSR is an acronym for "backslash R"\&.) This can be made the default when PCRE is built; if so, the other behavior can be requested through option \fIbsr_unicode\fR\&\&. These settings can also be specified by starting a pattern string with one of the following sequences:
.RS 2
.TP 2
.B
